============================================================
TEST 4: WHAT subspace of B₁ gives codimension 3?
============================================================

If dim(R) = 3 means dim(B₁) - dim(generators ∩ B₁) = 3, then at n=5
we need generators spanning dim(B₁)-3 = 6-3 = 3 dimensional subspace of B₁.
What natural 3D subspace of B₁ works?


Example: bits=41, bad=[1, 2, 4]
  dim(B₁) = 6, need codim-3 subspace = 3D
  If R = B₁ / <hidden lifts>: dim = 6 - 3 = 3
  rank(non-bad TTs) = 5
  codim of non-bad in B₁ = 1

============================================================
TEST 5: dim(ker(i_*)) for inclusion T\v → T
Grok claims ker(i_*: H_1(T\v) → H_1(T)) gives 3D global space
============================================================

For β₁(T)=0: ker(i_*: H_1(T\v) → H_1(T)) = H_1(T\v)
So dim(ker) = β₁(T\v) = 0 or 1
Σ_v ker(i_*) = Σ_v β₁(T\v) = #bad ≤ 3
This is just HYP-282 restated. Not a new mechanism.

